args: When I met Ilia, she was all alone—\njust a tiny, fragile thing.
But in a way, I was as well—and meeting\nher helped me to learn who I was and\ngrow stronger as a result.
And while she means everything to me,\nI fear the opposite is no longer true.
She's met her own special someone and\nfound a love across the boundaries of\nrace, just as I did with her.
I'm going home. Will you tell my father?
I'll take on whatever role he has for me\nand find a way to be of use.
What of her? It was always a given that\nwe would have to part ways eventually.\nIt's not something either of us can change.
Besides, she's all grown-up. Even normal\nparents send their children off eventually.
So it's time I grew up as well.\nI need to let her go.
She's...she's fine. I'm certain of it.\nShe's a grown woman, after all.
You say that, but I know you are worried\nalmost to the point of illness.
I have to trust her. What kind of mother\nwould I be if I refused to let her go?
You can trust in her and still worry.\nShe's important to you.
Mordecai's right. Take a long, hard look at\nyour feelings and come up with an answer\nthat feels right.
There's no set rule for what you ＂have＂ to\ndo. You and Ilia should find the answer\nthat's right for the two of you.
I'm going out to look for her.\nWhat will you do, Meene?
(Damn. I let my guard down because it\nwas a merchant I've dealt with for years.)
(That rat took one look at the bounty on\nmy head and sold me out to the army!)
(I've shaken some of them, but there are\nstill plenty on my tail... This isn't good.)
Hey! That's the thing from the other world!
Grab it along with the alchemist!
Because we were worried about you.
I'll make it back to you. You trust me, yes?
I don't think anyone's still following us,\nthanks to Mordecai. We're probably safe\nto walk for a—
That was a heck of a fall. Sort of a miracle\nI'm still in one piece.
Yes, it happened when I fell.
Don't be so chill about this!\nWhat do we DO?!
We wait. It isn't broken, which means\nit will heal up in time.
But wings are everything to a faerie!
Just let me hold you, child.\nI'm only glad you're safe.
I don't care about my wings—the only\nthought in my head was keeping you safe.
You would sacrifice yourself for me\nafter the terrible things I said to you?
I'm your mother, silly. Faerie, human,\narguments—none of that matters.
And though the ＂right＂ answer may be\nelusive, seeing my wings in this condition\nmakes one thing very clear...
You are the most precious thing in the\nworld to me, Ilia, and I love you.
I'm so sorry for all the trouble I've caused.\nI just wanted to become independent so\nthat you could go back home.
I thought if I did more work and made\nextra money, you wouldn't have to\nworry as much about me.
But I only made you worry MORE and then\nthis happened and... Well, I'm sorry.
I need to apologize to you as well;\nI was still treating you like a child.
I should have been your biggest believer,\nbut instead I pushed my own worries on to\nyou and tried to keep you under my guard.
I'm sorry you got saddled with\nsuch a clingy mother.
...We haven't exactly been making\nthings easy on one another, huh?
But you deserve a better daughter, and I\nknow you want to be the best mother you\ncan be, so we've got to get it together.
I got so caught up in what the right thing to\ndo was, I forgot to consider your feelings\nOR my own! What a fool I was.
...Hey, Mom? Thanks for raising me\nall these years.
Don't worry about me.\nChoose whatever is right for you\nso that you don't regret it.
I believe in you, child, and will support\nyou now and always.
It's Zethia and Mordecai! Over heeere!
(I thought I'd grown stronger, but I'm\nstill so weak. It seems I was just\ndependent on Ilia this whole time.)
(I need to become capable of living my life\neven without her.)
(That is the shape of my love:\nThe right answer for both of us.)
